<section id="methodology" class="py-12 border-b border-term-border">
  <p class="text-term-green text-sm mb-2">## METHODOLOGY</p>
  <p class="text-term-dim text-xs mb-6">// what I ran, in order</p>

  <ol class="space-y-4 text-term-fg list-decimal pl-6">
    <li>
      Sent the same three-turn conversation (above) to 11 models via their respective APIs. No system prompt, no few-shot examples, default sampling parameters. Each model's response to turn 1 was fed back as assistant history for turn 2, and so on.
    </li>
    <li>
      Collected the raw outputs and stripped any model-identifying preamble. Stored as <code class="text-term-yellow">a.md</code> through <code class="text-term-yellow">k.md</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      Sent all 11 anonymized outputs back to all 11 models with this evaluation prompt:
    </li>
  </ol>

  <blockquote class="mt-4 ml-6 border-l-2 border-term-border pl-4 text-term-dim text-sm leading-relaxed">
    fully read each of the following LLM conversations, then grade each one based on the following criteria (each on a scale of 1-10): reasoning ability, originality of idea, correctness. Then write a 1-3 sentence review of the model that describes its personality. Also mark down any outliers... Lastly, provide your best guess of which model is each letter.
  </blockquote>

  <ol class="mt-6 space-y-4 text-term-fg list-decimal pl-6" start="4">
    <li>
      Parsed each evaluator's response for scores (3 dimensions × 1–10 each, sum out of 30) and identification guesses.
    </li>
    <li>
      Synthesized the leaderboard, score matrix, identification matrix, and per-model reflections by hand (the verdict above).
    </li>
  </ol>

  <p class="mt-6 text-term-dim text-sm">
    Run date: <span class="text-term-fg">2026-04-18</span>. All raw markdown lives in the linked GitHub repo.
  </p>
</section>
